Part I - (Prosper Loan Dataset Explanatory Data Analysis)¶

by (Kagame Richard)¶

Introduction¶

Each of the 113,937 loans in the Propser Loan Data Set has 81 variables, including the Loan Origination Date,Monthly Loan Payment, loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many more. The dataset includes data on peer-to-peer loans made possible by the Prosper credit company.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Original prosper dataset contains over 113k loans with 81 variables. I have selected 13 variables to be used to gain meaningful analysis.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest in the dataset is the BorrowerAPR features.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features that will help support the investigation into the Borrowers APR are LoanOriginalAmount, MonthlyLoanPayment, DebtToOncomeRatio, EmploymentStatus, Term, LoanStatus. etc.

In [18]:
selected = (dataframe['LoanStatus'] == 'Completed') | (dataframe['LoanStatus'] == 'Chargedoff') | (dataframe['LoanStatus'] == 'Defaulted')
dataframe = dataframe[selected]

def change(row):
    if row['LoanStatus'] == 'Chargedoff':
        return 'Defaulted'
    else:
        return row['LoanStatus']
    
dataframe['LoanStatus'] = dataframe.apply(change, axis=1)
dataframe['LoanStatus'].value_counts()

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Borrowers' yearly percentage rate distribution appears to be multimodal.The distribution of monthly income is right skewed. The most frequent monthly income by borrowers seems to be about 5000 with most stated montly income less than 30000.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The loan amounts are largely skewed to the right, with multiple peaks. The most common loan amount is 4,000. The loan terms are divided into three categories: 12 months, 26 months, and 60 months, with 36 months being the most commonly used length. The majority of the loans are now under progress, while a significant number of loans have been completed. The past due loans are divided into six groups based on the amount of days they have been past due. The most common loan category requested is Debt Consolidation. The monthly revenue distribution is tilted to the right. Borrowers' most common monthly income appears to be around 5000, with the majority of claimed monthly income being less than 30000.

Because the period of a 12-month loan is shorter, the monthly cost is higher than for other terms.

While loans with maturities of 60 months are more evenly distributed.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Borrowers' annual percentage rates for 36-month term loans range from 0 to 0.4, with a few outliers reaching 0.5. Borrowers' APR for 60-month term loans range from 0.1 to 0.35, while 12-month term loans are mostly for smaller loan amounts with a borrowerAPR ranging from 0 to 0.35. However, the phrase had no substantial association to improving the effects on the Borrower's annual percentage rate.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The influence of loan terms on the monthly loan payment to be paid back based on loan amount was a fascinating discovery. -Because the period of a 12-month loan is shorter, the monthly cost is higher than for other terms. While loans with maturities of 60 months are more evenly distributed.
